for a win.\n\nFor wrong guesses, I deduct water and add weed. Win detection checks if all unique letters of the secret word are in guessed_letters after a correct guess, and loss detection triggers when remaining_water hits zero without having won yet.\n\nWriting the game logic... Finishing the error handling for the water function, then moving into the word selection logic that filters the word list by length constraints based on difficulty, with support for a custom random number generator.\n\nNow I'm setting up the game state dataclass and defining all the message constants for different game outcomes and validation errors.\n\nI'm implementing the core game functions: creating a new game with difficulty settings that initializes the word and water level, validating player input to ensure it's a single letter, and starting to build the logic for applying guesses to the game state. Continuing the game state update logic... Finishing the helper functions that check win/loss conditions and display the word state. Now I'm reconsidering the message constants — they should live in one place in game.py so tests can import them directly instead of duplicating the strings.\n\nFor the random functions, I'm using the module-level choice from the random module in words.py, which is correct. I'm also noticing that validate_guess needs to handle non-string inputs safely by checking the type first before stripping and validating.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the test cases I need to cover based on the spec — correct guesses revealing letters, incorrect guesses affecting water and weed counts, repeated guesses not penalizing again, input validation and normalization, win and loss detection, word masking, and word selection validation.\n\nFor the test implementation, I'll construct GameState objects directly with fixed values rather than relying on randomized constructors, and I'll inject a seeded random generator for any tests that touch randomness. I need to be careful about the `guessed_letters` set to avoid accidental state sharing between tests, but since `apply_guess` creates new sets each time, that should be safe.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the message constants against the spec — I need to map the exact strings from the examples like \"Good guess! The garden grows.\" to MSG_CORRECT, \"No match. A weed appears.\" to MSG_WRONG, and handle the already-guessed message as a format string. For the end-game messages, there's a win screen and a loss message about the garden running out of water.\n\nI should also clarify the GameState dataclass structure — since guessed_letters is a required field that gets passed in during initialization, I don't need to use field(default_factory=set), but I do need to make sure the type annotation works correctly with Python 3.10+ union syntax.\n\nFor the apply_guess function, when the game is already over, I'll return the same state with an appropriate message. I'm thinking \"The game is already over.\" works well as a clear, simple message that tells the player why their guess didn't register.\n\nI'm also considering whether to use `dataclasses.replace()` instead of manually constructing a new GameState — it's cleaner for cases where I'm only changing the message, and I can still pass `guessed_letters=set(state.guessed_letters)` explicitly when needed to avoid sharing mutable state. I'm mapping out how each case modifies the state: repeat and game-over guesses just update the message with a fresh set copy, correct guesses add the letter and potentially mark the game as won, and wrong guesses increment the weed count and decrement water while adding the letter. I think using `replace` with an explicit fresh set is the cleanest approach to avoid aliasing issues, so I'll import it and construct the returns that way.\n\nNow I'm planning the test suite, starting with a helper function to build game states with sensible defaults so I can easily create test fixtures.\n\nWriting test cases... Adding more test cases... Adding more test cases... Adding more test cases... Adding test cases for win/loss conditions... Writing test cases... Adding more test cases... I need to add a test for when a correct guess reveals multiple occurrences of the same letter in the word, like guessing \"E\" in \"SEEDLING\" should show both E's in the display. I'm also adding defensive tests for edge cases like None input to validate_guess, which should reject it and return an error message.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the files. I'll create the `__init__.py` files as empty or minimal, and I'm thinking about using message constants for repeated guesses that include the letter in the format string, so the message can dynamically show which letter was already guessed. So validate_guess only handles format validation, while apply_guess deals with repeated guesses. Since both empty and multi-character inputs use the same error message, I could define a single constant and alias it, or just keep them separate for flexibility. For `apply_guess`, the input letter is already validated as uppercase, but I'll add `.upper()` as a defensive measure anyway. For `is_won`, I need to check if all characters in the secret word appear in guessed letters, handling the edge case of an empty word. For `is_lost`, I'm checking if remaining water is at or below zero while not having won yet. I'll leave the `__init__.py` file empty since the task doesn't specify any exports. For imports in `game.py`, I'm using relative imports to work with the package structure. I'm also defining a message constant for the \"already guessed\" case and formatting it with the letter in both the apply_guess method and the corresponding test assertion.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all six files to complete the implementation, making sure everything aligns with the acceptance criteria around test discovery, compilation, no UI code in the package, correct GameState field names, and the water/weeds penalty logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason"